@149  = ~Reggik's second journal~
@150  = ~A short note is scribbled on the inside of the cover. I have decided to neither destroy nor to embellish these accounts. If I may be judged one day, these pages shall be my witnesses, for better or for worse.

4. Alturiak 1467

Breagar actually dared to do it! He asked Master Galthur for Audhild's hand. I've waited too long. This fool is getting in the way of my plans. I need to talk with Forres.

6. Alturiak 1467

Our plan is slowly coming to fruition. Forres is definitely the smarter of us two. It amazes me, how quickly he found a solution for our problem. Galthur was open to my suggestions, and gave Breagar a heck of challenge for his master's trial. He has to forge a ring of elements! But I shouldn't be too happy about this, I know that I will have to face the same challenge soon enough. I have to act quickly.

10. Tarsakh 1467

I'm making progress. Breagar is working obsessively. He doesn't even notice that he isn't the only one preparing to forge a ring of elements. I already reached out to my contacts in the south. My old clan is sure to help me.

15. Marpenoth 1467

Half a year of hard work, has paid off. My research is complete, and I assume Breagar has finished as well. It was so easy to manipulate his drawings of the ancient runes. A single stroke of a pen can turn the rune of control, into a rune of release. When he engraves the ring, the forces in the metal will be released and... I don't really like it, but sacrifices have to be made for the greater good. Breagar wouldn't understand it anyway.

20. Marpenoth 1467

Breagar wants to set out next spring. He decided to travel to the Sword Coast, to obtain a copy of the Book of Smithing in Candlekeep. That is fortunate. Entry into Candlekeep is expensive, and each day Breagar has to spend in order to gain enough money, is a day won for me.

1. Ches 1468

Breagar left yesterday. I will wait for a few day, just in case he comes back, then I too will ask Galthur for Audhild's hand. I am well prepared, knowing that a Book of Smithing is already waiting for me with my old clan.~
@151  = ~Reggik's first journal~
@152  = ~If someone ever reads this journal, I am surely dead. I deserve death according to dwarven law, because I have broken almost all laws of clan Bardormar, and I might have to break a few more in the future. But if this is my fated path, I shall walk it proudly, because it is a good path.

I met Forres, the duergar priest, a few weeks ago. He was stumbling through the mines, starving and mad, and killing him would have been easy. Yet something stayed my hand. I took him to an abandoned shaft and nursed him back to health. The longer I kept him hidden, the greater the danger, that someone could have found us. But likewise my certainty of doing the right thing also grow over time. Forres is a runaway slave, his entire clan has been conquered and subjugated by the drow. He had run through the many-branched tunnels of the Underdark until he came across the mines of clan Bardormar. If it hadn't been me who found him, but another dwarf – he surely would have been killed on the spot.

The more I cared about Forres and talked to him, the more I found my actions to be just. Forres is a duergar and thus an enemy of all Bardormar dwarves and some of his opinions run contrary to the teachings of the Mordinsamman. Yet he is reasonable and smart and I had more interesting in-depth discussions with him than with any pure dwarf.

It took some time until I realized that in my thoughts a great idea had taken root. I needed to end the feud between the gray dwarves and the clans and show Forres and his clan a way back into the fold of the Mordinsamman. No easy task, but I felt that my undertaking would find divine support. First I needed to succeed Galthur, to obtain the position of master smith. As a member of the clan's council, I would have great influence over the other dwarves, maybe enough to make a difference.

But now there is a new obstacle to my plans. Breagar the baker has decided to leave his father's bakery and became Galthur's new apprentice. It didn't take me long to figure out why. He has fallen in love with Audhild and wants to become the clan's Telormavar and because of this utter adolescent foolishness Breagar might ruin everything. I shall wait and see how things will turn out. If he should fail on his own, good. If not...~
@153  = ~Reggik's third journal~
@154  = ~Breagar and <CHARNAME> were seen in Athkatla! When Grothir reported that Breagar had failed his trial, but instead was touched by the gods, I already knew that our plan was on shakier grounds than I had thought. And yet... wouldn't a symbolic weapon like Berronar's Axe be exactly what the duergar need? It would give them something to believe in. Wouldn't it be a divine sign that would lead them back to the Mordinsamman?

I have hired One-Eyes Arnold, a weapon's trader, to fetch the axe. I don't even want to know how he did it, but he managed to acquire it during the chaos in Waukeen's Promenade. Gods willing, the loss of the axe will keep Breagar from Audhild and Galthur once and for all. At the same time it can give new hope for the duergar. I will leave the axe and the journals with Forres, before traveling to Trademeet to meet with Galthur. From there I shall travel to the halls of my old clan.~
